<section class="organizer-note">
  <h2 class="organizer-note__heading">A note from the Blue Ridge Ruby Embassy Organizer</h2>

  <p>
    As you go through this application, you'll realize how silly this whole
    thing is. My goal is for you to have fun with it and meet new people at
    the event.
  </p>

  <p>So a few things to know:</p>

  <ul class="organizer-note__list">
    <li>
      None of this is graded. No one's reading your answers looking for the
      "right" one. Take it as seriously as you want, or don't. We may give
      you a hard time during your embassy interview ;) but no pressure
    </li>
    <li>
      Everything is optional. If you're uncomfortable, don't do it. We'll
      accommodate you.
    </li>
    <li>
      Once you submit the application, you'll have a PDF to print out. The
      3rd page is your "Notarization" page. This is meant to be an
      icebreaker. Find someone at the event who matches the description in
      Part A, ask them the question in B.1, and have them write or draw
      their answer (drawing is funnier). Then have them sign B.2 with
      whatever they want&hellip; their real name, a fake name, their GitHub
      handle, their website, a drawing of the Blue Ridge Ruby logo,
      whatever sparks joy.
    </li>
    <li>
      If approaching a stranger feels weird, ask the volunteer staff to
      introduce you to someone, or look at the Schedule page to join a Meal
      or Activity to get to know people, or post on Slack. I think all
      attendees are pretty friendly and wanting to make friends :)
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If you need help, find me (Katya Sarmiento) or any embassy volunteer at
    the conference.
  </p>

  <p class="organizer-note__signoff">Welcome to the Blue Ridge Ruby Embassy.</p>
</section>
